nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tudor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Tudur</i>, a derivative of British Celtic <i>Toutorīx</i>, literally ‘people’ + ‘king’. It has sometimes been taken as a Welsh equivalent of Latin <i>Theodorus</i>, from Greek <i>Theodōros</i> ‘gift of God’ (see   Theodore  ), for which the usual Welsh form is <i>Tewdwr</i>.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Tudor</i>, a variant of <i>Teodor</i> (see   Theodore  ).","History: The Tudor royal family, English sovereigns from the accession of Henry VII in 1485 to the death of Elizabeth I in 1603, were of Welsh origin, being descended from Owain ap Maredudd ap Tudur, who held lands at Penmynydd in Anglesey."],"variants":[{"name":"Tutor","meanings":["Probably Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]},{"name":"Theodore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Serge, Henri, Pierre, Alide, Andre, Antoine, Benoit, Berthony, Chantal, Daphnee, Edouard, Guilene.","French and Mauritian (<b>Théodore</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Théodore</b>); English and Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."]},{"name":"Tedder","meanings":["English (Surrey): from the Middle English personal name <i>Thedere</i>, <i>Teddere</i>, which is either from the Old English personal name <i>Thēodhere</i> (from <i>thēod</i> ‘people’ + <i>here</i> ‘army’) or from the cognate ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theudher</i>, which seems to have been adopted by the Normans. Alternatively, perhaps it may be an occupational name from Middle English <i>teddere</i> ‘one who teds’, i.e. a person whose occupation was to spread mown grass for drying.","Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"The Fictitious Joan Tudor was born in 1453, in Glamorgan, Wales. She had at least 3 sons with William Ap Yevan Williams. She died in 1495, in Llanishen, Glamorgan, Wales, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1453–1495":"1453–1495","1443–1468":"1443–1468","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1466–1565":"1466–1565","1469–1508":"1469–1508","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","1565":"1565","1466":"1466","1465":"1465","1520":"1520","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","about 1466":"umbes 1466","1495":"1495","Dec 1469":"detsember 1469","1508":"1508","Llanishen, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanishen, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Tainton Hall, Thame, Oxfordshire, England":"South Oxfordshire, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1453–1495":"1453–1495","1443–1468":"1443–1468","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1466–1565":"1466–1565","1469–1508":"1469–1508","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","1565":"1565","1466":"1466","1465":"1465","1520":"1520","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","about 1466":"noin 1466","1495":"1495","Dec 1469":"joulukuu 1469","1508":"1508","Llanishen, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanishen, Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Tainton Hall, Thame, Oxfordshire, England":"South Oxfordshire, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1453–1495":"1453–1495","1443–1468":"1443–1468","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1466–1565":"1466–1565","1469–1508":"1469–1508","1469":"1469","1468":"1468","1565":"1565","1466":"1466","1465":"1465","1520":"1520","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","about 1466":"environ 1466","1495":"1495","Dec 1469":"décembre 1469","1508":"1508","Llanishen, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanishen, Glamorgan, Galles","Wales":"Galles","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Galles","Tainton Hall, Thame, Oxfordshire, England":"South Oxfordshire, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"The Fictitious Joan Tudor est née en 1453, à Glamorgan, Galles. Elle